sec.p:
The first record of the giant pill-millipede genus
Prionobelum Verhoeff, 1924
from Thailand , with the integrative description of two species ( Diplopoda , Sphaerotheriida , Zephroniidae )

Thailand
lies within the Indo-Burmese biodiversity hotspot and contains a wealth of endemic species, many of them still awaiting description (

). This diversity is imperiled by a suite of factors, chief among them deforestation (

). While 23% of the country’s land lies within a network of protected areas, these are highly fragmented and remain subject to both human exploitation and climate change (

; 

). Scientists and policy makers are thus in a 
race against
time to describe and protect the country’s many endemic species (

).

Thailand possesses a highly diverse millipede fauna, much of it very recently described. The number of species rose from 105 in the penultimate checklist from 2005 (
) to 263 in the updated version from 2023 (
). Of these at least 222 are endemic or subendemic to Thailand (
).

The giant pill millipedes (order 
Sphaerotheriida
) of 
Thailand
are placed within the family 
Zephroniidae
, the only family of the order found in Southeast Asia (

). Thailand’s 13 species have heretofore been restricted to two genera: 

Zephronia
Gray, 1832

with nine species, eight of them described in the past three years (

; 

; 

; 

) and 

Sphaerobelum
Verhoeff, 1924

with four species, three of them described in the past two years (

; 

; 

). This is still lower than the number of 
Zephroniidae
species found in neighboring 
India
, 
Vietnam
and 
Laos
(

; 

; 

, 

). The pace of recent discoveries, however, suggests that the inventory in 
Thailand
is far from complete.

In this contribution we provide the first record of the genus
Prionobelum Verhoeff, 1924
from Thailand . The genus was previously only known from Vietnam and, especially, China (
). We describe two species, one of which is found at over 2000 m above sea level on the northeastern Doi Inthanon, the highest point in Thailand , while the other is found near the Malaysian border in the low-lying Bang Lang National Park (
;
). We describe both species integratively, combining morphology with genetic barcodes. A molecular genetic barcoding study was undertaken to place these species in a tree relative to all Zephroniidae species for which COI sequences are presently available.

Map
: The localities of the described species were mapped in ArcGIS 3.1.0 (

). All basemaps used are licensed to ESRI (Environmental Systems Research Institute, Inc).

Dissection, light microscopy, illustrations and habitus photographs
: Dissection was done under a Zeiss Discovery V12. All terminology follows the recent literature (

). Illustrations were produced by hand using paper and pencil with a camera lucida mounted on a Zeiss SteREO Discovery V12. Drawings were then inked to tracing paper with Pigma Micron pens sizes 04 and 005. Illustrations were scanned, touched up in Adobe Photoshop 2023 and assembled into plates in Adobe Illustrator 2023.

DNA barcoding
: In order to find relatives, match males to females, and investigate the intraspecific and interspecific genetic distances of the here described species, a molecular genetic barcoding study (

) was conducted. The DNA extraction, amplification, and sequencing protocol was similar to that employed in earlier studies (

; 

), using the degenerate primer pair HCO-JJ/LCO-JJ (HCOJJ AWACTTCVGGRTGVCCAAARAATCA / LCOJJ CHACWAAYCATAAAGATATYGG) (

). BLAST searches (

) were performed to confirm sequence identities. Sequences were concatenated by hand or utilizing the software Seqman (DNASTAR Inc.). The whole dataset was translated into amino acids to rule out the accidental amplification of pseudogenes. The six new sequences have been uploaded to GenBank under the accession codes: PP297645–267650 (Table 1).

Phylogenetic and distance analyses
: The 6 new COI sequences were added to a dataset from a previous study, containing all published COI sequences of the 
Zephroniidae
restricted to 2 sequences per species, of which there were 50 (by 11.2023), in addition to 2 far- and 4 near-outgroups (

; 

). As no COI sequences of the genus 

Prionobelum

were published on Genbank, the COI gene of a potential Chinese 

Prionobelum

was extracted from a previously published full mitogenome (

) and added to our dataset. All sequences were aligned in Bioedit (

). The final dataset contained 63 terminals and 673 base pairs (Table 1).

The best fitting substitution model for a maximum likelihood analysis was calculated with Modeltest (

) as implemented in MEGA11. The best fitting model was the general time reversible (GTR)-Model (

) with gamma distribution and invariant sites (GTR+G+I) (lnL=-12638.954, Invariant=0.398, Gamma=0.648, Freq A: 27.28, T: 33.54, C: 23.19, G: 15.98).

Evolutionary history was inferred by using the Maximum Likelihood method under the General Time Reversible model (GTR+G+I) (

). The tree with the highest log likelihood (112638.95) is shown in 
Fig. 1
. Initial trees for heuristic search were automatically obtained by applying Neighbor-Join and BioNJ algorithms to a matrix of pairwise distances estimated using the Maximum Composite Likelihood (MCL) approach. Codon positions included were 1st-2nd-3rd. All positions with less than 95% site coverage were eliminated, i.e., fewer than 5% alignment gaps, missing data, and ambiguous bases were allowed at any position (partial deletion option). There were a total of 637 positions in the final dataset. The bootstrap consensus tree was calculated from 1000 replicates (

) in MEGA11 (

). The obtained tree was edited in Adobe Illustrator 2023 with all bootstrap values>50% illustrated (
Fig. 1
).

